    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-06-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-06-30T15:00:00-05:00" n="393"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d393">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/3309: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-30T17:00:00-03:00"
                            >June 30, 1943—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1451. I have learned that the British Embassy in telegram sent London yesterday
                    attributed to this Embassy the opinion that change in Argentine foreign policy
                    might begin with severance of relations with Japan. By way of explanation I
                    desire to say that about 3 weeks ago, my Brazilian colleague told me that he
                    thought the new Government might well commence with Japan as latter was first to
                    attack an American country and later break with Germany as having attacked
                    Brazil. I recall mentioning this conjecture to Hadow<note n="21"
                        xml:id="d393fn21">Robert Henry Hadow, British Counselor of Embassy in
                        Argentina.</note> who apparently thought it was based on information
                    received by us from a more authentic source.</p>
                <p>There is, of course, possibility Argentine Government might follow some such
                    procedure in case of Japan as there are few Japanese in this country expecting
                    thereby to precipitate a break by the Germans and feeling that by then the
                    Italians might have collapsed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
